{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Use British English|date=January 2013}} <!-- CHECK THE TALK PAGE BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO DELETE/REDIRECT THIS ARTICLE!! --> {{Infobox song | name = Exogenesis: Symphony | cover = MuseExogenesis.jpg | alt = | type = single | artist = [[Muse (band)|Muse]] | album = [[The Resistance (album)|The Resistance]] | released = 17 April 2010 | format = [[12-inch single|12"]] | recorded = 2008–09 | studio = Studio Bellini {{small|([[Lake Como]], Italy)}} | venue = | genre = {{hlist|[[New prog]]|[[symphonic rock]]|[[space rock]]<ref>http://www.nme.com/news/muse/35085</ref>|[[rock opera]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Leahey |first=Andrew |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r1636853 |title=The Resistance - Muse |publisher=AllMusic |date=2009-09-14 |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>}} | length = {{ubl|4:18 {{small|(Part 1 - "Overture")}}|3:56 {{small|(Part 2 - "Cross-Pollination")}}|4:37 {{small|(Part 3 - "Redemption")}}|'''12:51 {{small|(total length)}}}}''' | label = {{hlist|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]|[[Helium 3 (record label)|Helium-3]]}} | writer = [[Matt Bellamy]] | producer = [[Muse (band)|Muse]] | prev_title = [[Resistance (song)|Resistance]] | prev_year = 2010 | next_title = [[Neutron Star Collision (Love Is Forever)]] | next_year = 2010 | misc = {{Extra track listing | album = [[The Resistance (album)|The Resistance]] | type = studio | prev_track = I Belong to You | prev_no = 8 | track = Exogenesis | track_no = 9–11 }} }} "'''Exogenesis: Symphony'''", commonly known as simply "'''Exogenesis'''", is a song by English [[alternative rock]] band [[Muse (band)|Muse]], featured on their 2009 fifth studio album ''[[The Resistance (album)|The Resistance]]''. Written by lead vocalist, guitarist and pianist [[Matthew Bellamy]] over the course of a number of years, the song is presented as a [[symphony]] in three [[Movement (music)|movement]]s entitled <!-- Please do not edit these titles, they are correct!! -->"Overture", "Cross-Pollination" and "Redemption", respectively, each occupying a separate track at the end of the album and spanning nearly 13 minutes in total. "Exogenesis" was released as a [[Single (music)|single]] in the United States on 17 April 2010, with 500 copies to be made available by import in the United Kingdom through the band's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muse.mu/shop/product/245/exogenesis/menu/4/singles/ |title=Exogenesis - 12 |publisher=[[Muse (band)|Muse]] |accessdate=26 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403005002/http://muse.mu/shop/product/245/exogenesis/menu/4/singles/ |archivedate=3 April 2010 }}</ref>
On 30 October 2012, an official music video directed by Japanese comedian Tekken was released for ''Redemption'', the third part of the Exogenesis Symphony.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XPBfaMsA97o</ref>
==Background and composition== A song in the long, symphonic style of "Exogenesis" was first hinted at as a possible inclusion for Muse's fifth studio album in early 2008, when British music magazine ''[[NME]]'' quoted Bellamy as revealing that "I think on the next album I’d like to do at least one 15-minute [[space rock]] solo."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/muse/35085 |title=Muse: next album to have '15-minute space rock solo' |publisher=''[[NME]]'' |date=12 March 2008 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref> This idea was later discussed further and in a more extreme sense, when Bellamy suggested that the band may reject the conventional [[album]] format in favour of releasing a series of [[Single (music)|single]]s, or indeed "one 50-minute symphony."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/muse/36945 |title=Muse begin work on fifth album |publisher=''[[NME]]'' |date=29 May 2008 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref>
As the band confirmed that recording had begun for the album in late 2008, Bellamy explained more about the symphonic song, which he revealed would be in three parts on the album:
{{cquote|There is a new song in three parts, more of a symphony than a song, which I have been working on sporadically for many years [...] As a large percentage of the composition is orchestral, I have never wanted to collaborate with a string arranger as they may make it 'theirs'. So I have been arranging the orchestral elements myself, which is taking a long time. It should hopefully make the next album as the final three tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/muse/41287 |title=Muse aim to include 'hardest song ever' on new album |publisher=''[[NME]]'' |date=26 November 2008 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref>}}
With the presence of "Exogenesis", among other songs, Bellamy hinted at the [[Classical music|classical]] direction taken by the band in writing and recording ''The Resistance'', describing the record as "A symphonic album" and joking that "We'll be knocking on [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]'s door, you know?"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/news/muse/43149 |title=Muse: 'Our new album is set for Classic FM' |publisher=''[[NME]]'' |date=2 March 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref>
Speaking for the [[iTunes LP]] feature for ''The Resistance'', Bellamy said the following about the inspirations and meanings of "Exogenesis":
{{cquote|["Exogenesis: Symphony"] is influenced by [[Sergei Rachmaninoff|Rachmaninov]], [[Richard Strauss]], [[Frédéric Chopin|Chopin]] and [[Pink Floyd]]. It looks at the concept of '[[panspermia]]'. It is a story of humanity coming to an end and everyone pinning their hopes on a group of astronauts who go out to explore space and spread humanity to another planet. Part 1 is a jaded acceptance that civilization will end. Part 2 is a desperate hope that sending the astronauts to find and populate other planets will be successful alongside the recognition that this is the last hope. Finally, Part 3 is when the astronauts realize that it is just one big cycle, and recognize that unless humanity can change it will happen all over again.}}
==Release and reception== On 3 July 2009, Muse revealed, via their [[Twitter]] page, the track listing for ''The Resistance''; the "Exogenesis" was shown to occupy the final three tracks of the album, with the three parts being dubbed "Overture",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/muse/status/2459545233 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305165117/https://twitter.com/muse/status/2459545233 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=5 March 2016 |title=9. EXOGENESIS : SYMPHONY P ... |author=[[Muse (band)|Muse]] |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=3 July 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }} </ref> "Cross-Pollination"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/muse/status/2459923378 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317050112/https://twitter.com/muse/status/2459923378 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=17 March 2016 |title=10. EXOGENESIS : SYMPHONY ... |author=[[Muse (band)|Muse]] |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=3 July 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }} </ref> and "Redemption",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/muse/status/2460273928 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305185553/https://twitter.com/muse/status/2460273928 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=5 March 2016 |title=11. EXOGENESIS : SYMPHONY ... |author=[[Muse (band)|Muse]] |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=3 July 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }} </ref> respectively.
The song has been acclaimed by critics. In a pre-release interview with the band, ''NME'' identified "Exogenesis" as one of the highlights of the album, describing it as "more bombastic than anything Muse have ever previously done" and revealing that it features "classical piano from Bellamy and a full orchestra throughout."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.muselive.com/index.php?m=single&id=4726 |title=Muse in NME |publisher=Muselive (quoting ''[[NME]]'') |date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712062611/http://www.muselive.com/index.php?m=single&id=4726 |archive-date=12 July 2009 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> French media source ''JudeBox'' reviewed the album before its release, comparing Bellamy's vocal performance to that of [[Radiohead]] frontman [[Thom Yorke]] and identifying classical composers [[Frédéric Chopin]] and [[Franz Liszt]] as influences for the symphony.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.muselive.com/forums.php?m=posts&p=1568373#1568373 |title=Re: The Resistance Mini-Review |publisher=Muselive |date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' quoted Bellamy as revealing that the song features an [[orchestra]] of over 40 musicians,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v356/turkeyleader/musemojo.jpg |title=Muse: Progressive stadium rock three dream up album five |last=Wilkinson |first=Roy |publisher=''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref> while ''NME'' praised the "classical piece [...] put together by [[Matthew Bellamy]] over the course of many years" as the "Most astonishing and over-the-top of all" the songs on ''The Resistance''.<ref name="nme">{{cite news |url=http://www.muselive.com/forums.php?m=posts&p=1593522#1593522 |title=The Italian Job |publisher=''[[NME]]'' |accessdate=23 July 2009 }}</ref> The feature article quoted bassist and backing vocalist [[Christopher Wolstenholme]] as saying the following on the song:
{{cquote|You can always just take the band away from that track and just have the orchestral bit and it would still be beautiful. I just think it's a stunning piece of music and we've never done something like that before, where you've got all these songs that are in different movements. The orchestra were the main bit of the song and the band was more of a backdrop. The strings were at the forefront. It's fucking astonishing.<ref name="nme"/>}}
Drummer [[Dominic Howard]] was quoted as adding the following to the description of "Exogenesis":
{{cquote|It's a real journey that song as well. It’s kind of... you can’t really hear what Matt’s singing in the first part much, but the whole song is about leaving the destructive planet we’ve created, leaving it behind to go populate somewhere else in the universe. So it's a big journey anyway, it's a big kind of filmic, visual journey as well.<ref name="nme"/>}}
On possibly performing the song live, Bellamy was quoted simply as enthusiastically declaring that "We’ll give it a go!"<ref name="nme"/> For most shows of [[The Resistance Tour]], "Overture" has been a staple and is usually played at the start of an encore, leading into "[[Stockholm Syndrome (Muse song)|Stockholm Syndrome]]".{{cn|date=September 2015}}
"Exogenesis: Symphony" was released on 17 April 2010 in the US on 12" vinyl only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theprp.com/category/releases/ |title=Releases |publisher=THEPRP |accessdate=23 March 2010 }}</ref>
"Exogenesis: Symphony Part I" was used for [[Dior Homme]]'s advertisement called "A Rendezvous", directed by [[Guy Ritchie]] and starring [[Jude Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodbackwash.com/video-jude-law-for-dior-homme-directed-by-guy-ritchie-music-by-muse/ |title=Video: Jude Law for Dior Homme -Directed By Guy Ritchie-Music By Muse |publisher=HollywoodBackwash.com |accessdate=8 December 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909161721/http://www.hollywoodbackwash.com/video-jude-law-for-dior-homme-directed-by-guy-ritchie-music-by-muse/ |archivedate=9 September 2010 }}</ref>
==Lawsuit controversy==
In September 2012, three years after the release of ''The Resistance'' and "Exogenesis", Charles Bollfrass claimed that the "Symphony" copied his original cinematic project with the same name. Speaking to a Manhattan court, Bollfrass stated that he had developed a "cinematic science-fiction rock opera" titled "Exogenesis" when he contacted the band in 2005, as well as the rock band [[System of a Down]], to compose the film's original score. The following year, Muse told him they were not interested in pursuing the project, but System of a Down's lead guitarist, [[Daron Malakian]], had said yes, announcing his band's hiatus during an MTV interview.<ref>http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1530066/system-down-plan-hiatus-after-ozzfest.jhtml</ref> Bollfrass was seeking $3.5 million in damages.<ref>http://www.entlawdigest.com/2012/09/06/1772.htm</ref>
Concerning the lawsuit, [[Muse (band)|Muse]] stated "The claim is complete nonsense, and is categorically denied. It appears to be based on a 'screenplay' which the band never received or saw, produced by someone the band has never heard of. It speaks volumes that the album in question was released a full three years ago, and yet this is the first that has been heard of these groundless allegations."<ref>http://kroq.cbslocal.com/2012/09/11/lawsuit-alert-did-muse-really-rip-off-a-sci-fi-writer-for-their-album-the-resistance/</ref>
The lawsuit was finally dismissed in April 2013 by Judge [[Louis L. Stanton]] after an earlier attempt to dismiss had failed in 2012. In dismissing the case, Judge Stanton held that Bollfrass' claims had "practically no legal or factual basis." "The similarity of the two works here lies in their concepts, abstracted to a high degree of generality," Judge Stanton wrote. "Both works are based on a concept of planetary breakdown and space travel, but their treatment is markedly different."<ref>http://articles.law360.s3.amazonaws.com/0429000/429520//mnt/rails_cache/https-ecf-nysd-uscourts-gov-cgi-bin-show_doc-pl-caseid-401143-de_seq_num-49-dm_id-11262284-doc_num-13.pdf</ref>
"Bollfrass also said the cover art for "The Resistance" featured an image from the storyboards of his screenplay." But while Judge Stanton tossed the lawsuit, he denied Warner Music's request for attorneys' fees, saying "there was no evidence to conclude that Bollfrass' complaint was frivolous."<ref>http://www.law360.com/articles/429520/warner-music-escapes-copyright-suit-over-muse-song</ref>
==Live performances== The symphony is also noted for its live performances; despite the fact that "Cross-Pollination" has not been played live, "Overture" has been performed at virtually every date on [[The Resistance Tour]], besides festival appearances (although it had been played at one or two of the festival slots, this was however rare). "Redemption" was finally played for the first time ever in January 2013 in Saitama, Japan.<ref name="Exo pt. 3 Live">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0qaZVqo-6JE] Exogenesis Part 3 Live at Saitama Super Arena, Japan</ref> Live performances during arena dates would usually take place during the first song of the encore set and would involve the band performing on the towers which comprised the arena tour's stage design, as they slowly rose up and blue lighting covered the stage. However, during later dates, the song was sometimes used as the concert opener, although this was rare. Stadium performances were more notable however, as the band would release a UFO into the crowd whilst the song was being played.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cochrane |first=Greg |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/11281742 |title=Newsbeat - Rockers Muse bring UK 'UFO' tour to a close at Wembley |publisher=BBC |date=2010-09-13 |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> The UFO would circle the stadium and, as [[Matt Bellamy]]'s vocals started, an acrobat in the guise of an alien would drop out of the bottom of the UFO and begin performing acrobatics above the audience. This was also a notable event in Muse's live career, as the band had tried and failed on previous tours to secure a UFO to use in live performances, only to have their plans foiled because of health and safety issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/news/2010/muses-ufo-banned-from-t-in-the-park |title=Muse’s UFO Banned From T In The Park |publisher=Xfm |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>
