This article aims to compile various depictions of [[Miami]] in [[popular culture]].
==In literature== * ''[[Back to Blood]]'' by [[Tom Wolfe]]. * ''[[Big Trouble (novel)|Big Trouble]]'' by [[Dave Barry]]. * ''[[Breaking Point (novel)|Breaking Point]]'' by [[Alex Flinn]] * ''[[The Demon in the Sun Parlor]]'' by [[Lester Goran]] * ''[[Detective (novel)|Detective]]'' by [[Arthur Hailey]] * ''[[Dreaming in Cuban]]'' by [[Cristina García (journalist)|Cristina García]] * ''[[Florida Roadkill]]'' by [[Tim Dorsey]] * ''[[The Island of Eternal Love]]'' by [[Daína Chaviano]] * ''[[Loving Che]]'' by [[Ana Menéndez]] * ''[[Miami (book)|Miami]]'' by [[Joan Didion]] * ''[[Pronto (novel)|Pronto]]'' by [[Elmore Leonard]] * ''[[Retribution (novel)|Retribution]]'' by [[Jilliane Hoffman]] * ''[[Rum Punch]]'' by [[Elmore Leonard]] * ''[[The Saint in Miami]]'' by [[Leslie Charteris]] * ''[[Threat Vector]]'' by [[Tom Clancy]] and [[Mark Greaney (novelist)|Mark Greaney]] * ''[[Tourist Season (novel)|Tourist Season]]'' by [[Carl Hiaasen]] * ''[[Trace (novel)|Trace]]'' by [[Patricia Cornwell]] * ''[[The White Dress]]'' by [[Mignon G. Eberhart]]
==In movies== <small>Note: this list includes movies showing different perspectives of Miami; does not include all films shot in Miami. Please see [[List of films and television shows set in Miami]] for a complete list of films.</small> * ''[[2 Fast 2 Furious]]'' (2003) set and shot in Miami. * ''[[Absence of Malice]]'' (1981) Set and shot in Miami and Coral Gables, including inside the since-demolished Miami Herald building on Biscayne Bay * ''[[Absolute Zero (film)|Absolute Zero]]'' (2006) set in Miami * ''[[Ace Ventura: Pet Detective]]'' (1994) a 1994 American [[comedy film]] starring [[Jim Carrey]] as [[Ace Ventura]], an animal detective who is tasked with finding the abducted dolphin who is the mascot of the US football team [[Miami Dolphins]]. * ''[[All About the Benjamins]]'' (2002) set in Miami * The ''[[Bad Boys (franchise)|''Bad Boys'' series]]'', is a [[film series|series]] of [[action film|action]] [[comedy film]]s created by [[George Gallo]]. It stars [[Martin Lawrence]] and [[Will Smith]] as two detectives in the [[Miami Police Department]], Marcus Burnett and Mike Lowrey. ** ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]'' (1995) ** ''[[Bad Boys II]]'' (2003) ** ''[[Bad Boys II#Sequel|Bad Boys for Life]]'' (2020) * ''[[Baywatch (film)|Baywatch]]'' (2017) set and shot in [[South Beach]] * ''[[The Birdcage]]'' (1998) set in [[Miami]]. The main character, Armand Goldman, is the openly gay owner of a [[Drag queen|drag club]] in South Beach called ''The Birdcage'' * ''[[Caddyshack]]'' (1980) Boating scene filmed in [[Biscayne Bay]]; balance of filming done in various area of the [[Miami Metropolitan Area]] * ''[[Cocaine Cowboys]]'' (2006) a [[documentary film]] directed by [[Billy Corben]], and produced by Alfred Spellman and Billy Corben through their Miami-based media studio [[Rakontur]]. The film explores the rise of [[cocaine]] and the [[Miami Drug War]] (the resulting crime epidemic that swept the [[United States|American]] city of [[Miami]], in the 1970s and 1980s). The producers of ''Cocaine Cowboys'' use interviews with [[Law enforcement agency|law enforcers]], [[journalist]]s, [[lawyer]]s, former [[drug smuggler]]s, and [[gang member]]s to provide a first-hand perspective of the Miami drug war. * ''[[Dostana (2008 film)|Dostana]]'' (2008) The first [[Bollywood]] movie to be filmed entirely in Miami, United States<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1185420/ |title=Dostana (2008) |publisher=www.imdb.com |accessdate=2010-06-28 }}</ref> * ''[[Marley & Me]] (2008) The film was shot on location in [[Miami]], [[West Palm Beach]], [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]], and [[Dolphin Stadium]] * ''[[Miami Vice (film)|Miami Vice]]'' it is an [[Film adaptation|adaptation]] of the 1980s [[Miami Vice|television series of the same name]] * ''[[Moonlight (2016 film)]]'' set and shot in the [[Liberty City (Miami)|Liberty City]] neighborhood of [[Miami]]. At the [[74th Golden Globe Awards]] ''Moonlight'' won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Drama|Best Motion Picture – Drama]] and was nominated in five other categories. The film won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]], along with [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Ali and [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] for Jenkins and McCraney, from a total of eight nominations. * ''[[Reno 911!: Miami]] (2007) Set and shot in Miami * ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]'' (1983) the [[cult film|cult classic]] tells the story of Cuban refugee [[Tony Montana]] ([[Al Pacino]]) who arrives in 1980s Miami with nothing and rises to become a powerful drug kingpin. * ''[[Step Up Revolution]]'' (2012) Set and shot in Miami * ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'' (1998) Set and shot in Miami. The film was placed 27th in the [[American Film Institute]]'s ''[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs|100 Years, 100 Laughs: America's Funniest Movies]]'', a list of the 100 funniest movies of the 20th century. In 2000, readers of ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine voted it the fourth-greatest comedy film of all time. * ''[[Transporter 2]] (2005) Set in Miami * The [[Wild Things (film series)|''Wild Things'' series]] is a [[film series|series]] of [[Erotic Thriller]] films created by Stephen Peters. The films are set and shot in the Miami area. ** ''[[Wild Things (film)|Wild Films]]'' (1998) ** ''[[Wild Things 2]]'' (2004) ** ''[[Wild Things: Diamonds in the Rough]]'' (2005) ** ''[[Wild Things: Foursome]]'' (2010)
==In music== {{see also|List of songs about Miami}} * The 1998 [[Will Smith]] song [[Miami (Will Smith song)|Miami]] is about the city of Miami. The music video was shot and filmed in Miami. * Miami native and rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] has paid homage to Miami in many of his songs over the years. * Miami-influenced, [[Gloria Estefan]] and the [[Miami Sound Machine]], hit the popular music scene with their Cuban-oriented sound and had hits in the 1980s with "Conga" and "Bad Boys".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6731031/rewinding-the-charts-in-1985-miami-sound-machine-did-the-conga|title=Rewinding the Charts: In 1985, Miami Sound Machine Did the 'Conga' in Its Debut|website=Billboard|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> * [[Miami Bass]], [[Miami Bass]] spawned artists like [[2 Live Crew]] (featuring Uncle Luke), 95 South,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.95southmusic.com/bio/|title=Bio|website=95 South Music|access-date=June 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012204857/http://www.95southmusic.com/bio/|archive-date=October 12, 2016|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Tag Team,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World Volume 8: Genres: North America|last=Shepherd|first=John|publisher=A&C Black|year=2012|isbn=1441160787|location=Google Books|page=325}}</ref> 69 Boyz,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/69-boyz-booty-and-miami-bass-super-fest-at-bankunited-center-6483532|title=69 Boyz, Booty, and Miami Bass Super Fest at BankUnited Center|last=Gonzalez|first=Victor|date=October 29, 2012|website=Miami New Times|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> Quad City DJ's, and Freak Nasty. Examples of these songs are "Whoomp! (There It Is)" by Tag Team in 1993, "Tootsee Roll" by 69 Boyz in 1994, and "C'mon N' Ride It (The Train)" by the Quad City DJ's in 1996.
==In TV series== <small>Note: this list includes TV shows showing different perspectives of Miami; does not include all shows shot in Miami. Please see [[List of films and television shows set in Miami]] for a complete list of TV shows.</small> * ''[[Ballers]]'' [[HBO]]series set in Miami * ''[[Dexter (TV Series)]]'' [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series based entirely in Miami * ''[[Charlie's Angels (2011 TV series)|Charlie's Angels]]'' the 2011 reboot is set in Miami instead of the West Coast. * ''[[Flipper (1964 TV series)|Flipper]]'' was filmed in Miami at Greenwich Studios (at the time called Ivan Tors Studios) at 12100 Ivan Tors Boulevard in Miami and at [[Key Biscayne, Florida]]. The show was produced in cooperation with the [[Miami Seaquarium]], an aquarium also located on Key Biscayne in Miami. * The critically acclaimed American [[sitcom]] ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' revolves around four older single women (three widows and one divorcée) sharing a house in Miami, Florida. * ''[[Jersey Shore (TV series)]]'' (Season 2) was set and shot in Miami which aired in 2010. * ''[[Miami Vice]]'' is an American television [[crime drama]] series created by [[Anthony Yerkovich]] and executive produced by [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] for [[NBC]]. The series starred [[Don Johnson]] as [[James "Sonny" Crockett]] and [[Philip Michael Thomas]] as [[Ricardo Tubbs|Ricardo "Rico" Tubbs]], two [[Miami-Dade Police Department|Metro-Dade Police Department]] detectives working undercover in [[Miami]]. The series ran for five seasons on NBC from 1984 to 1989. * ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' focuses on a cutting-edge, controversial [[plastic surgery]] center and follows the personal and professional lives of its founders [[Sean McNamara (Nip/Tuck)|Dr. Sean McNamara]] and [[Christian Troy|Dr. Christian Troy]] (portrayed by [[Dylan Walsh]] and [[Julian McMahon]] respectively). Seasons 1-4 are based in Miami.
==In video games== * [[Miami]] or ''Vice City'' is one of the three main levels of the first game of the [[Grand Theft Auto|video game franchise]], [[Grand Theft Auto (video game)|Grand Theft Auto]]. * ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' the game is loosely based on Scarface and is entirely set in 1986 Miami * ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City Stories]]'' is the prequel to ''GTA: Vice City'' and takes place in a 1984 Miami. * ''[[Driver (video game)|Driver]]'' and ''[[Driver 3]]'' feature various parts of the city. * The [[cult video game]] ''[[Hotline Miami]]'' is entirely based in 1989 Miami. * ''[[Hotline Miami 2: Wrong Number]]'' is both a prequel and sequel to the original game. * ''[[Scarface: The World Is Yours]]'' based on the [[Scarface (1983 film)|1983 film]] is entirely set in Miami. * ''[[Street Racing Syndicate]]'' features a level in Miami.
